Reference-contexts: The actual process of combination itself is straightforward. Since a group of refinements is generated to solve each incorrect behaviour, all possible combinations, where one refinement is chosen from each group, are generated. However, this is immediately followed by a repeat of KRUSTs usual refinement filtering <ref> (Craw & Sleeman, 1995) </ref>. This is necessary, for example, to remove duplicate refinements generated when a single fault leads to many incorrect behaviours. Conicting combinations of refinements are also removed.
